Hey Lila,

Did you know that light comes from the sky?

AND HAVE YOU THOUGHT OF THE RAMIFICATIONS?

I know, I know. I kind of sound like this guy:

I'm actually just talking about the sun though
But think about it.

When light comes from the sky, it:

* Casts shadows below things
* Makes the top of things brighter
* Makes the undersides of things darker

Even though our screens are flat, designers invest a great amount
of time into making many elements on them appear 3-D =E2=80=93 and the
above are the rules they use.

=E2=80=8B
Buttons are popped out from the screen =E2=80=93 but these rules apply
equally to things pressed into the screen.

=E2=80=8B
And even in a flat design, these rules still apply =E2=80=93 just more
subtly.

For instance, content cards should always be lighter than their
backgrounds. This is because they=E2=80=99re popped out from the surface
of the screen, and therefore catch the sun=E2=80=99s rays better =F0=9F=98=
=8E

=E2=80=8B
(This is a super common beginner mistake, since design apps start
with white frames, and it seems only natural to add a gray card
on top)

=E2=80=8B
Really internalizing that light comes from the sky was one of the
first big breakthroughs I had as a beginning designer. In fact, I
wrote about it in 7 Rules for Creating Gorgeous UI (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/4zuq65w5k0heh3zgl8ax/reh8hohqxzn369c2/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9sZWFybnVpLmRlc2lnbi9ibG9nLzctcnVsZXMtZm9yLWNyZWF0aW5nLWdvcmdlb3VzLX=
VpLXBhcnQtMS5odG1s
) =E2=80=93 an article that went viral back in 2014, and paved the way
for this very newsletter!

It's also one of the many "soundbite lessons" I include in Learn
UI Design. I strongly believe that if I can leave every student
with practical and memorable short phrases that apply widely
across their design career, they will be better designers much
quicker than trying to learn via more theoretical approaches.

